{"title":"Vision-Language Interpreter for Robot Task Planning","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Language-guided robot planners can generate opaque and logically fragile action sequences, while symbolic planners require explicit, machine-readable PDDL problem descriptions (objects, initial state, goals) that are hard to derive automatically from natural-language instructions and visual scenes.","method":"Introduce ViLaIn, a modular vision-language interpreter that generates full PDDL problem descriptions from a linguistic instruction and a scene image without additional training. It (1) detects task-relevant objects using an open-vocabulary detector (Grounding-DINO) with domain-knowledge–augmented text queries (e.g., “round cutting board,” “kitchen knife”) to form PDDL objects; (2) infers the initial state by captioning each detected object with BLIP-2 and prompting GPT-4 with few-shot examples to synthesize PDDL predicates; and (3) derives the goal specification by prompting GPT-4 with the instruction plus the estimated objects and initial state. The assembled PD is then passed to a symbolic planner (Fast Downward) to obtain a plan, yielding interpretable, planner-verifiable task specifications."},{"problem":"Automatically generated PDDL problems often contain syntactic inconsistencies or contradictory/insufficient predicates that make planning fail; manual debugging breaks scalability and interpretability.","method":"Propose Corrective Re-prompting (CR) with Chain-of-Thought: when Fast Downward returns an error, ViLaIn re-prompts GPT-4 with the original inputs, the generated PD, the planner’s error message, and few-shot exemplars; GPT-4 first explains the error (CoT) and then outputs a refined PD. This loop is repeated up to n times, substantially improving robustness. In ablations on the cooking domain, removing CR drops Rsyntax/Rplan/Rall from 0.99/0.99/0.71 to 0.60/0.18/0.09, and removing CoT further degrades performance, demonstrating that planner-feedback–guided, reasoning-based refinement is critical."},{"problem":"There is no standard multimodal benchmark or general metrics to evaluate PDDL problem generation quality across domains.","method":"Release the ProDG dataset spanning three domains (Cooking, Blocksworld, Hanoi) with paired instructions, scene images, and PDDL domains/problems, and introduce four domain-agnostic metrics: Rsyntax (VAL-based syntactic correctness), Rplan (valid plan existence via Fast Downward), Rpart (recall of objects/initial/goal parts), and Rall (all-parts exact recall). On ProDG, ViLaIn achieves ≥99% Rsyntax across domains and Rplan of 0.99 (Cooking), 0.94 (Blocksworld), and 0.58 (Hanoi), quantifying strengths and remaining challenges in PD generation."}]}
